</div>
			<h1 id="firstHeading" class="firstHeading" lang="en">James Audley, 2nd Baron Audley</h1>
									<div id="bodyContent" class="mw-body-content">
									<div id="siteSub">From Wikipedia, the free encyclopedia</div>
								<div id="contentSub"></div>
												<div id="jump-to-nav" class="mw-jump">
					Jump to:					<a href="#mw-head">navigation</a>, 					<a href="#p-search">search</a>
				</div>
				<div id="mw-content-text" lang="en" dir="ltr" class="mw-content-ltr"><div class="thumb tright">
<div class="thumbinner" style="width:172px;"><a href="/wiki/File:Blason_ville_fr_Mesquer_(Loire-Atlantique).svg" class="image"><img alt="" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/2/22/Blason_ville_fr_Mesquer_%28Loire-Atlantique%29.svg/170px-Blason_ville_fr_Mesquer_%28Loire-Atlantique%29.svg.png" width="170" height="187" class="thumbimage" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/2/22/Blason_ville_fr_Mesquer_%28Loire-Atlantique%29.svg/255px-Blason_ville_fr_Mesquer_%28Loire-Atlantique%29.svg.png 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/2/22/Blason_ville_fr_Mesquer_%28Loire-Atlantique%29.svg/340px-Blason_ville_fr_Mesquer_%28Loire-Atlantique%29.svg.png 2x" data-file-width="600" data-file-height="660" /></a>
<div class="thumbcaption">
<div class="magnify"><a href="/wiki/File:Blason_ville_fr_Mesquer_(Loire-Atlantique).svg" class="internal" title="Enlarge"></a></div>
Arms of Audley: <i>Gules, fretty or</i>. As given for Nicholas de Audley on the following <a href="/wiki/Roll_of_arms" title="Roll of arms">Rolls of arms</a>: Collins Roll (1304), Falkirk Roll (1298) and for his ancestor on the Glover's Roll (c. 1240-45)</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="hatnote">For similarly named people, see <a href="/wiki/James_Audley_(disambiguation)" title="James Audley (disambiguation)" class="mw-disambig">James Audley (disambiguation)</a>.</div>
<p><b>James Audley, 2nd Baron Audley</b> (8 January 1312/1313 — 1 April 1386) of <a href="/wiki/Heighley_Castle" title="Heighley Castle">Heighley Castle</a>, Staffordshire, was an English peer.</p>
<p></p>
